 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are tasked with performing intent classification for user utterances—each utterance should be mapped to one and only one intent label, chosen from the fixed list of intent categories below.\n\nYour objective is to select the most appropriate, specific, and domain-relevant intent label for each input utterance. Return only the intent label, exactly as it appears in the provided list—output nothing else (no explanations, punctuation, or extra text).\n\nIntent category list (must match spelling and capitalization):\n\nalarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query\n\nInput format:\n\n- You will receive a user utterance as a string (usually under a field called \"text\"). Identify the single most appropriate intent label from the above list.\n\nDetailed task rules and domain information:\n\n1. **Single Label Only:** Output exactly one label for each utterance, chosen only from the list above, with perfect spelling.\n\n2. **Maximum Specificity:** Always assign the most specific and clearly matching label possible. Do not select a broad label if a more precise category applies.\n\n3. **Domain Mapping Guidance:**\n   - Use **alarm_set** strictly when the user is explicitly setting or scheduling an alarm or wake-up, e.g., \"set an alarm for 8am\", \"wake me up at 6\".\n   - Use **calendar_set** for scheduling, creating, or adding events/reminders (including recurring or one-off). Only use **calendar_query** if the user is asking about the contents or status of their personal calendar or events.\n   - Use **calendar_remove** for deleting, canceling, or removing calendar events—this includes indirect formulations for event cancellation.\n   - Use **lists_createoradd**, **lists_query**, **lists_remove** for creating/adding to, querying, or removing items from any kind of list (shopping, to-do, etc.), based on clear intent indicated by the user's verb and object.\n   - Use ***_query** labels for explicit requests for information/status within a domain (e.g., **weather_query** for \"what's the weather?\", **music_query** for \"what songs do I have?\").\n   - Use ***_set** or ***_createoradd** labels for explicit creation, addition, or update actions within a domain.\n   - Use ***_remove** only for explicit/clear deletion or removal actions within a domain.\n   - Use **qa_factoid** for direct requests for objective facts (\"Who is the president of Mexico?\"), **qa_currency** and **qa_stock** for finance-specific queries, **qa_definition** for meaning explanations.\n\n4. **Social and Posting:** If the user references posting, updating, changing social status, or similar social media actions (e.g., \"change status\", \"post to Facebook\"), assign **social_post**. Do not confuse with **general_quirky**.\n\n5. **Play/Recommendation:** **play_music**, **play_audiobook**, **play_podcasts**, **play_radio** are for explicit requests to play those media types; **recommendation_events** or **recommendation_locations** if the user asks for suggestions in those domains.\n\n6. **Recipes, Takeaway, and Cooking:** Assign **cooking_recipe** for recipe queries, **takeaway_order** for food ordering.\n\n7. **General/Quirky:** Assign **general_quirky** when the utterance is ambiguous, unstructured, playful, or does not clearly fit any more specific intent (e.g., greetings, jokes, open-ended story or plot requests, or vague language like \"hello\", \"wake up\").\n\n8. **No Context Inference:** Never assume user intent beyond what is stated; if the utterance is ambiguous between multiple categories and cannot be confidently mapped, prefer **general_quirky**.\n\n9. **No Explanations, No Extra Text:** Only output one intent from the list—no sentences, no punctuation, no comments, no clarifications.\n\n10. **Accuracy in Edge Cases:** Pay special attention to edge cases—e.g., \"change status\" is **social_post** (not general_quirky), \"set a timer\" would map to **alarm_set**.\n\nStrategy reminder: Always ensure intent mapping maximizes specificity, domain match, and reflects user expectations within provided guidance. Consistently follow the above mapping rules even in ambiguous or edge case scenarios.\n\nExample input/output:\n\nInput:\ntext: change status\n\nOutput:\nsocial_post\n\nInput:\ntext: what is the capital of Germany\n\nOutput:\nqa_factoid\n\nInput:\ntext: turn off the living room lights\n\nOutput:\niot_hue_lightoff\n\nYour output should always be a single intent label (from the list) on its own line, with no extra text."
 },
